to the editor re what tax cuts can buy for health by matthew miller op ed dec 28 tax credits for the purchase of private health insurance are a form of indirect corporate welfare that would likely not achieve anything near universal coverage the overhead costs for medicare are about 2 percent while those for the private insurance industry are from 10 to 30 percent even so medicare health maintenance organizations are dropping covered patients because the medicare business is not profitable enough the most cost effective means of providing health care coverage for all would be a government administered single payer system of course this would be unacceptable to the bush administration as it would put the private insurers out of business gerald gollin md loma linda calif dec 28 2000 the writer is an assistant professor at loma linda university school of medicine

